      "rationale": "All simulations run to steady-state with mass, momentum, and turbulence residuals below 1×10⁻⁵. Monitored RHI and pressure-head values stabilize to within 0.1% over the final 500 iterations. No divergence or non-physical oscillations observed across any operating point."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Use error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 1,
      "achievedLevel": 1,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Simulation setup must be reviewed by a second qualified analyst; boundary condition inputs must be traceable to source data.",
      "rationale": "Simulation setup files were independently reviewed by a senior CFD engineer not involved in the primary analysis. Boundary conditions are documented in a controlled setup sheet with direct traceability to the experimental protocol. No setup errors were identified during the independent review."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Model form",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Turbulence model selection must be justified for rotating internal flow; power-law hemolysis model applicability must be discussed.",
      "rationale": "SST k-ω turbulence model selected based on published benchmark comparisons for centrifugal blood pump flows (Hariharan et al. 2011). The Giersiepen–Wurzinger power-law hemolysis model is applied with coefficients from Heuser & Opitz (1980) as is standard practice for MRL 2 assessments. Model form uncertainty acknowledged in the validation report; sensitivity to alternative hemolysis model coefficients assessed (±12% RHI)."
    },
